1
00:00:49,960 --> 00:00:51,325
Breathe, my love.

2
00:00:51,560 --> 00:00:55,201
Don't be afraid.
I'm right here with you.

3
00:00:59,240 --> 00:01:03,006
Another deep, cleansing
breath, my love.

4
00:01:06,640 --> 00:01:10,201
And now a little push.

5
00:01:24,120 --> 00:01:26,691
We did it! An egg!

6
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:28,451
MY EGG

7
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:31,011
Our egg.

8
00:01:31,880 --> 00:01:35,009
And what a perfect egg it is.

9
00:01:35,200 --> 00:01:38,329
With a perfect child inside.

10
00:01:41,960 --> 00:01:44,645
Just a little look, ko-hoh,
at my new arrivals.

11
00:01:44,880 --> 00:01:47,611
No, no, my dear.
They need warmth for survival.

12
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:51,043
- Just a little peak, ko-hoh.
- Move your nosy beak, ko-no.

13
00:01:51,240 --> 00:01:53,607
Oh, this waiting, this anticipating...

14
00:01:53,800 --> 00:01:56,485
...the birth of my perfect baby swan.

15
00:01:57,520 --> 00:01:59,284
Our swans, dear.

16
00:01:59,520 --> 00:02:01,409
Oh, yeah.

17
00:02:02,320 --> 00:02:05,005
<i>Three perfect eggs
Won't my kids be super</i>

18
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:07,686
<i>Wish that I could look inside
And see their future</i>

19
00:02:07,920 --> 00:02:10,321
<i>Will you be leaders
The pride of the flock</i>

20
00:02:10,840 --> 00:02:13,002
<i>Three little chips
Off of my old block</i>

21
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:16,010
<i>Well an apple doesn't fall
Too far from the tree</i>

22
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:17,964
<i>You'll be the spittin' image of me</i>

23
00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:20,686
<i>- Spittin' image of him, spittin' image
- That's right</i>

24
00:02:20,920 --> 00:02:23,048
<i>- Spittin' image of him
- Oh, boy.</i>

25
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:26,005
<i>All I ask is perfection
From my sons and daughters</i>

26
00:02:26,200 --> 00:02:29,124
<i>Like my humble self
And all the swans before us</i>

27
00:02:29,360 --> 00:02:31,601
<i>We're gonna ko-hoh best of them all</i>

28
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:34,127
<i>Everyone will listen
When our trumpets call</i>

29
00:02:34,360 --> 00:02:36,886
<i>You'll be my reflection
Everyone will see</i>

30
00:02:37,120 --> 00:02:39,043
<i>You'll be the spittin' image of...</i>

31
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:41,203
<i>-...me
- Spittin' image of him, spittin' image</i>

32
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:43,124
<i>- Indeed
- Spittin' image of him</i>

33
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:45,806
<i>Do you remember when we courted?</i>

34
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:48,844
<i>- How we were dancing beak to beak</i>
- I do

35
00:02:49,080 --> 00:02:51,731
<i>I entranced you with my call</i>

36
00:02:51,960 --> 00:02:54,884
<i>- And I made your life complete
- Here, let me take a seat.</i>

37
00:02:55,080 --> 00:02:58,323
<i>He can't wait till he sings
So the world will know</i>

38
00:02:58,560 --> 00:03:01,404
<i>We're the best ko-hohers
In the whole ko-hoh so</i>

39
00:03:01,640 --> 00:03:03,881
<i>Hush, dear mama, I'm in ecstasy</i>

40
00:03:04,120 --> 00:03:06,600
<i>They'll be the spittin' image of me</i>

41
00:03:06,960 --> 00:03:09,486
<i>The apple can't fall
Too far from the tree</i>

42
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:12,291
<i>They'll be the spittin' image of me</i>

43
00:03:12,520 --> 00:03:14,727
<i>Be the spittin' image of him</i>

44
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:17,440
Shoo-doop
The spittin' image of her

45
00:03:17,800 --> 00:03:20,406
<i>Shoo-doop
The spittin' image of him</i>

46
00:03:20,960 --> 00:03:23,486
<i>An apple doesn't fall
Too far from the tree</i>

47
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:27,611
<i>- You'll be the spittin' image of me
- You'll be the spittin' image of me</i>

48
00:03:28,360 --> 00:03:29,361
<i>Oh, yeah</i>

49
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:32,207
- You're on my foot.
- Oh, no.

50
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:49,808
At last, I am a father
with all the pleasant duties...

51
00:03:50,040 --> 00:03:52,884
...and awesome responsibilities
of fatherhood.

52
00:03:53,880 --> 00:03:58,329
Welcome, my children,
to this magnificent pond...

53
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,685
...and the swamp adjacent.

54
00:04:05,680 --> 00:04:08,286
Oh, you have chops, my little one.

55
00:04:08,520 --> 00:04:10,966
I shall call you Ella.

56
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:16,367
Ko-hoh, my mama done and hatched me.

57
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:18,130
You have good pipes...

58
00:04:18,360 --> 00:04:21,603
...and bad grammar.

59
00:04:22,080 --> 00:04:24,890
I shall call you Billie.

60
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:32,006
A son.

61
00:04:32,240 --> 00:04:34,481
My own blessed son!

62
00:04:34,960 --> 00:04:37,691
Welcome, my child,
to wind and weather.

63
00:04:37,920 --> 00:04:40,048
I'll... I'll...
I'll name you Louie...

64
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:42,806
...after my father, Louie,
and his father, Louie-Louie.

65
00:04:43,400 --> 00:04:46,483
In the tradition of the great
swans before you...

66
00:04:46,760 --> 00:04:49,206
...let me hear your ko-hoh!

67
00:04:52,040 --> 00:04:53,405
<i>Louie'?</i>

68
00:04:55,560 --> 00:04:58,006
Perhaps he's shy, dear.

69
00:04:58,440 --> 00:05:00,249
No need to be shy, son.

70
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,049
We are all waiting to hear
your ko-hoh, Louie.

71
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,721
There, there...
There must be a mistake.

72
00:05:23,600 --> 00:05:27,764
This child cannot be ours!
Someone must have switched the eggs.

73
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:29,849
Of course he's ours.

74
00:05:30,520 --> 00:05:32,090
He's our Louie.

75
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:36,246
But my son is destined to be
the greatest of all the trumpeters.

76
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:38,960
Why, just look
at his superior parentage.

77
00:05:39,560 --> 00:05:41,847
How will he ever speak
to his friends?

78
00:05:42,200 --> 00:05:43,611
Or attract a mate'?

79
00:05:44,120 --> 00:05:47,203
After all, what made you fall in love
with me was my...

80
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:51,450
...deep, powerful, resonant voice.

81
00:05:52,920 --> 00:05:56,527
A father wants so much
for his children...

82
00:05:56,760 --> 00:05:58,489
...and now this.

83
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:02,011
Oh, a tragedy. What despair!

84
00:06:04,080 --> 00:06:06,003
- What is it'?
- It's a boy.

85
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:07,281
Another son'?

86
00:06:07,520 --> 00:06:08,885
No, no, darling.

87
00:06:09,400 --> 00:06:12,847
We are being watched by a human boy.

88
00:06:14,280 --> 00:06:15,930
And with such big eyes.

89
00:06:27,480 --> 00:06:30,643
- Marco'?
- Polo.

90
00:06:31,640 --> 00:06:34,610
- Marco'?
- Polo.

91
00:06:34,880 --> 00:06:37,804
- Marco'?
- Polo.

92
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:41,051
No fair. Louie didn't say "Polo."

93
00:06:41,440 --> 00:06:42,965
Well, he can't talk.

94
00:06:43,560 --> 00:06:44,800
Can't talk'?

95
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,241
And he calls himself a trumpeter swan?

96
00:06:47,480 --> 00:06:49,801
I don't think so.

97
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:51,650
Louie can't help it.

98
00:06:51,880 --> 00:06:53,609
Father says he's...

99
00:06:53,800 --> 00:06:55,609
...you know, defective.

100
00:06:55,960 --> 00:07:00,602
Well, defective one,
Marco Polo is a talking game.

101
00:07:00,800 --> 00:07:03,849
And if you can't talk,
you can't play.

102
00:07:04,080 --> 00:07:06,401
Those are the rules, buddy.

103
00:07:08,400 --> 00:07:11,449
Hey! If you can't talk,
you can't play.

104
00:07:11,960 --> 00:07:14,247
You're out of here, duckie.

105
00:07:15,480 --> 00:07:18,086
A trumpeter swan who can't trumpet?

106
00:07:18,440 --> 00:07:22,001
Oh, man, breaks my heart.

107
00:07:22,200 --> 00:07:24,009
Okay, here we go.

108
00:07:29,560 --> 00:07:32,006
My swan dive!

109
00:07:36,080 --> 00:07:41,007
And now, Serena's all-time,
world famous cannonball!

110
00:07:42,960 --> 00:07:46,851
One, two, three...

111
00:07:47,080 --> 00:07:48,445
...here I go!

112
00:07:57,840 --> 00:08:00,571
Hi. You want a slice of pond weed?

113
00:08:01,960 --> 00:08:03,610
I'm Serena. What's your name?

114
00:08:07,200 --> 00:08:10,170
That's your name? No way!

115
00:08:12,680 --> 00:08:13,681
Hey!

116
00:08:14,440 --> 00:08:18,001
You could say goodbye, Mr...

117
00:08:22,320 --> 00:08:24,049
It's not fair.

118
00:08:24,280 --> 00:08:26,567
Everyone has a voice but me.

119
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:35,282
You got the beat, honey.
Want to join in'?

120
00:08:35,920 --> 00:08:38,002
If only they knew how much.

121
00:08:38,200 --> 00:08:40,601
- Sorry.
- Now see what you did?

122
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:42,484
Well, I said I was sorry.

123
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:45,684
It's not my fault he's, you know...

124
00:08:48,360 --> 00:08:50,328
The fox! I've gotta warn them.

125
00:08:52,400 --> 00:08:54,482
Billie! Ella! Look out!

126
00:08:57,840 --> 00:08:59,046
Please let them hear me!

127
00:09:03,160 --> 00:09:06,243
Thank goodness you are safe,
my precious daughters.

128
00:09:06,480 --> 00:09:08,164
Oh, how my heart trembled.

129
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:09,601
Look!

130
00:09:10,280 --> 00:09:12,408
That human boy...

131
00:09:12,760 --> 00:09:14,728
...saved the lives of our children.

132
00:09:15,320 --> 00:09:18,403
He has my eternal gratitude.

133
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:21,723
When I think of what could have
happened with Louie unable...

134
00:09:21,920 --> 00:09:25,766
...to cry out a warning. Although
I'm sure you did your best, son.

135
00:09:26,080 --> 00:09:27,366
I did try.

136
00:09:27,880 --> 00:09:29,609
Can't he see how hard I tried'?

137
00:09:30,280 --> 00:09:33,204
Everyone okay? That was close.

138
00:09:37,800 --> 00:09:38,801
Hey, no problem.

139
00:09:47,600 --> 00:09:51,002
<i>Okay, campers, lights out, please.</i>

140
00:09:54,960 --> 00:09:58,806
I could spend the whole day
watching the baby swans.

141
00:09:59,640 --> 00:10:02,644
There are three cygnets.
Two of them said, "Beep."

142
00:10:04,240 --> 00:10:05,890
The third one didn't.

143
00:10:06,120 --> 00:10:08,202
I like him the best.

144
00:10:08,400 --> 00:10:11,210
I wonder why baby birds beep?

145
00:10:12,960 --> 00:10:15,566
"Why do baby birds beep?"

146
00:10:16,040 --> 00:10:18,884
Is that all you can
think about, bird boy'?

147
00:10:19,280 --> 00:10:21,408
What's it to you, A.G.?

148
00:10:24,280 --> 00:10:25,611
Swans are fowl!

149
00:10:26,120 --> 00:10:30,409
Besides, some of us are trying
to sleep. So get a life, will you!

150
00:10:38,280 --> 00:10:41,204
<i>She's so fine
She blows my mind, yeah</i>

151
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:42,447
Hey, little guy.

152
00:10:42,680 --> 00:10:43,806
I'm Sam Beaver.

153
00:10:44,040 --> 00:10:46,168
You like music. Me too.

154
00:10:47,920 --> 00:10:51,003
<i>Everybody sing along</i>

155
00:10:51,280 --> 00:10:54,602
<i>We're gonna rock, baby
All night long</i>

156
00:10:55,400 --> 00:10:56,481
Now you try it.

157
00:10:57,840 --> 00:10:59,046
You can't sing?

158
00:10:59,280 --> 00:11:02,170
So what? Not everybody
can do everything.

159
00:11:02,600 --> 00:11:05,809
But I bet you're
a better swimmer than me.

160
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:08,207
Wait till he sees this!

161
00:11:16,240 --> 00:11:18,481
I'm not really big on pond shrubbery.

162
00:11:19,600 --> 00:11:22,410
Something stinks out here!

163
00:11:24,520 --> 00:11:28,002
And your feathered friend
doesn't smell too good either.

164
00:11:28,200 --> 00:11:30,601
You're pathetic, Beaver.

165
00:11:32,720 --> 00:11:33,721
Thanks.

166
00:11:37,080 --> 00:11:40,004
Hey, I like you too, little guy.

167
00:11:49,920 --> 00:11:54,801
<i>I got the freezin', breezin'
Low-down blues</i>

168
00:11:55,360 --> 00:11:59,649
The chill you feel is the result
of the onset of autumn...

169
00:11:59,880 --> 00:12:03,521
...a subject about which
I have a few timely remarks.

170
00:12:05,960 --> 00:12:08,201
Have you ever wondered, children...

171
00:12:08,440 --> 00:12:12,968
...why we swans have wings attached
to our rather handsome torsos?

172
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:15,202
Not really, Father.

173
00:12:16,160 --> 00:12:20,927
These mighty wings allow us to migrate
to more temperate waters.

174
00:12:23,760 --> 00:12:26,206
Fly south to a warmer lake.

175
00:12:26,680 --> 00:12:28,444
Oh, gotcha!

176
00:12:29,120 --> 00:12:30,849
But we don't know how to fly.

177
00:12:31,080 --> 00:12:34,129
As your father, I shall teach you.

178
00:12:34,360 --> 00:12:38,843
First, I extend my long, elegant neck.

179
00:12:40,560 --> 00:12:44,281
Then I retract my muscular feet.

180
00:12:45,800 --> 00:12:49,088
Then I pump my glorious wings.

181
00:12:50,920 --> 00:12:54,845
And finally, I call out
a mighty ko-hoh...

182
00:12:55,080 --> 00:12:57,401
...when I take to the sky.

183
00:12:58,000 --> 00:12:59,809
I have to ko-hoh?

184
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:02,401
Now I'll never be able to fly.

185
00:13:02,800 --> 00:13:03,961
Come on.

186
00:13:04,520 --> 00:13:06,807
Well, I'm gonna try.

187
00:13:09,080 --> 00:13:10,605
Amazing!

188
00:13:10,840 --> 00:13:13,127
Those guys down there look like ants.

189
00:13:14,080 --> 00:13:18,608
Those are ants, silly.
You haven't left the ground yet.

190
00:13:38,320 --> 00:13:39,481
That's it, Ella.

191
00:13:45,920 --> 00:13:47,729
You're getting it, Billie.

192
00:13:47,920 --> 00:13:51,003
Louie, I can't help but notice
you're not in the air.

193
00:13:53,440 --> 00:13:55,169
You must try, son.

194
00:13:59,240 --> 00:14:00,605
Look at us, Father.

195
00:14:01,320 --> 00:14:04,449
Coming, girls.
You sound marvellous!

196
00:14:06,120 --> 00:14:07,963
Okay, I'll try.

197
00:14:13,160 --> 00:14:15,401
Hey, I'm flying.
I can do it!

198
00:14:15,640 --> 00:14:17,005
Whoa!

199
00:14:19,920 --> 00:14:22,651
Look at me, Father.
Oh, please, look at me.

200
00:14:24,920 --> 00:14:28,129
Stay in your own lane, buster.
You should have honked.

201
00:14:28,720 --> 00:14:30,802
That kid's a menace!

202
00:14:31,160 --> 00:14:34,801
You must keep your eye
on the sky, my boy.

203
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:39,927
And I must find my son a voice.

204
00:14:45,400 --> 00:14:48,324
I remember you.
You're the one who can't talk.

205
00:14:48,840 --> 00:14:51,730
<i>How does it feel'? Is it weird'?</i>

206
00:14:51,960 --> 00:14:54,804
You know, I bet it makes you
a great listener.

207
00:14:55,840 --> 00:14:58,002
Hey, want to see my triple gainer'?

208
00:15:05,920 --> 00:15:07,604
Did you like that?

209
00:15:08,600 --> 00:15:10,648
Boy, am I silly.

210
00:15:10,880 --> 00:15:14,327
You can't talk,
and I'm asking you questions.

211
00:15:14,560 --> 00:15:16,085
I'm the one who's weird.

212
00:15:18,080 --> 00:15:20,811
She's not weird. She's great!

213
00:15:21,280 --> 00:15:25,524
This sounds crazy, but I think
that little swan really understood me.

214
00:15:26,040 --> 00:15:28,611
I wonder if I'll ever see him again.

215
00:15:31,280 --> 00:15:32,406
There you are.

216
00:15:32,640 --> 00:15:36,201
Good luck, little guy.
Have a nice winter!

217
00:15:37,480 --> 00:15:40,404
I wonder how birds know
which way is south?

218
00:15:41,160 --> 00:15:42,685
Do they follow the stars'?

219
00:15:43,600 --> 00:15:46,410
How do they know which way is south?

220
00:16:03,760 --> 00:16:05,285
There it is, my children.

221
00:16:05,480 --> 00:16:06,561
Our new home.

222
00:16:06,760 --> 00:16:09,411
Red Rock Lake, Montana.

223
00:16:12,200 --> 00:16:14,202
Last one there's a rotten egg.

224
00:16:18,680 --> 00:16:20,887
Come on, Louie, let's explore.

225
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:23,208
She's inviting me.

226
00:16:29,920 --> 00:16:31,809
I have good news for you, darling.

227
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:35,766
Before you know it, your son, Louie,
will be in love.

228
00:16:36,280 --> 00:16:39,409
Why... Why...
Why this is terrible news.

229
00:16:39,880 --> 00:16:41,245
Love isn't terrible.

230
00:16:41,600 --> 00:16:45,525
It is if you can't say ko-hoh
to the female of your choice.

231
00:16:45,760 --> 00:16:49,970
And you have to spend the rest
of your life in loneliness and misery.

232
00:16:50,560 --> 00:16:52,528
Oh, you do have a point, my love.

233
00:16:52,920 --> 00:16:54,729
I have many points...

234
00:16:54,960 --> 00:16:57,850
...but I am Louie's devoted father.

235
00:16:58,640 --> 00:17:00,244
I shall act.

236
00:17:01,320 --> 00:17:03,448
I hear there are man-made devices...

237
00:17:03,680 --> 00:17:06,923
...that produce sound similar
to our wild trumpeting.

238
00:17:07,160 --> 00:17:10,050
Similar but inferior, of course.

239
00:17:10,280 --> 00:17:15,002
I shall search
for such a device for our son.

240
00:17:15,200 --> 00:17:18,647
Even if I have to go
to the ends of the earth.

241
00:17:19,040 --> 00:17:23,602
If I may make a suggestion, dear,
just got to Billings, Montana.

242
00:17:23,800 --> 00:17:25,609
It's a lot closer.

243
00:17:26,200 --> 00:17:30,205
All right. Very well, without
further ado, I will go to Billings.

244
00:17:31,040 --> 00:17:34,362
Goodbye, my love. Ko-hoh!

245
00:17:34,920 --> 00:17:38,891
What a swan. I just hope
he knows what he's doing.

246
00:17:56,240 --> 00:17:59,483
How do human females put up
with these annoying love calls?

247
00:18:01,280 --> 00:18:05,444
Oh, my. Who would want to mate
after hearing that?

248
00:18:08,760 --> 00:18:13,607
Aha. Now that is the sound
of romance.

249
00:18:30,640 --> 00:18:34,406
Aha. Now is my time to act.

250
00:18:34,640 --> 00:18:36,642
May luck go with me.

251
00:18:39,280 --> 00:18:42,443
Correction. May good luck go with me.

252
00:18:42,680 --> 00:18:44,205
Here I go!

253
00:18:51,880 --> 00:18:53,609
Somebody help me!

254
00:19:04,640 --> 00:19:08,087
Help, I've been robbed
by a swan thief.

255
00:19:08,320 --> 00:19:11,403
I'll get you, you miserable thief.

256
00:19:11,640 --> 00:19:14,769
Thief? Me'? A lowly thief.

257
00:19:15,880 --> 00:19:18,804
I did it for my son.

258
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:21,651
I only did it for my son, Louie!

259
00:19:32,120 --> 00:19:36,603
Okay, mister, let's stop what we're
doing and hand over that weapon.

260
00:19:36,920 --> 00:19:39,400
All right, I'm issuing you
a citation, little man.

261
00:19:39,640 --> 00:19:42,291
It is illegal to shoot here.
Oh, yes.

262
00:19:42,520 --> 00:19:45,842
This happens to be a bird refuge.
Can you read, sir'? Can you'?

263
00:19:46,160 --> 00:19:48,891
Right there, there is a sign.
It says, "no hunting."

264
00:19:49,080 --> 00:19:51,924
Right here. Black and white.
"N-O H-U-N ting."

265
00:19:52,120 --> 00:19:54,805
What would that be'?
Say, no hunting, perhaps.

266
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:56,411
It is illegal to shoot.

267
00:19:56,600 --> 00:19:58,011
The coast is clear.

268
00:19:58,200 --> 00:20:00,567
Saved by the written word.

269
00:20:01,880 --> 00:20:04,565
Oh, hey there.
I'm Sweets. Who are you'?

270
00:20:09,280 --> 00:20:10,884
Hey, now I remember you.

271
00:20:11,080 --> 00:20:13,128
The one who can't talk.

272
00:20:13,320 --> 00:20:15,527
Oh, baby, don't feel bad.

273
00:20:15,880 --> 00:20:17,609
Everybody's got something.

274
00:20:19,800 --> 00:20:21,450
You like those words, baby?

275
00:20:22,760 --> 00:20:24,728
Look. Humans have words...

276
00:20:24,960 --> 00:20:26,610
...all over the place.

277
00:20:26,840 --> 00:20:28,001
On their food.

278
00:20:28,440 --> 00:20:30,568
On their tails.

279
00:20:31,840 --> 00:20:34,241
Even on their mountains.

280
00:20:34,600 --> 00:20:37,809
They can communicate
without even speaking.

281
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:41,004
Wow! This is great news!

282
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:42,565
What did I do?

283
00:20:42,800 --> 00:20:45,280
Wait a minute, little fella,
where you going?

284
00:20:55,240 --> 00:20:56,480
This is so exciting.

285
00:20:56,720 --> 00:20:58,802
I have to try to tell him.

286
00:20:59,440 --> 00:21:02,683
There's this thing
called reading and writing.

287
00:21:02,920 --> 00:21:04,570
And I have this human friend...

288
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:06,684
...who can show me how.

289
00:21:06,920 --> 00:21:09,764
What? You're not making
yourself clear, my boy.

290
00:21:10,320 --> 00:21:13,802
Then I won't be, you know,
defective anymore.

291
00:21:14,440 --> 00:21:16,807
I wish you could speak to me, Louie.

292
00:21:17,760 --> 00:21:21,765
What wonderful things you would say.

293
00:21:22,240 --> 00:21:26,006
He can't understand me now,
but one day he will.

294
00:21:28,040 --> 00:21:31,044
What? What? What? What?
Louie? Louie? Wait, Louie?

295
00:21:31,560 --> 00:21:33,289
Come back, son! Look!

296
00:21:33,640 --> 00:21:36,484
I brought you a voice!

297
00:21:39,320 --> 00:21:41,926
<i>Another chilly day here in Billings.</i>

298
00:21:42,280 --> 00:21:46,569
<i>So bundle up, stay home,
and get out the hot cocoa.</i>

299
00:21:49,320 --> 00:21:54,247
<i>Cinderella dressed in yellow
Went upstairs to kiss her fellow</i>

300
00:21:58,240 --> 00:21:59,730
What?

301
00:22:00,400 --> 00:22:02,402
Whoa! It's you.

302
00:22:02,640 --> 00:22:04,404
It can't be.

303
00:22:06,280 --> 00:22:07,805
It is you.

304
00:22:08,400 --> 00:22:10,562
Well, little guy,
how did you find me'?

305
00:22:12,560 --> 00:22:14,722
What? You stepped
in bear droppings?

306
00:22:18,560 --> 00:22:20,642
"No hunting."

307
00:22:21,280 --> 00:22:22,247
I agree.

308
00:22:22,480 --> 00:22:23,686
Why shoot animals?

309
00:22:23,920 --> 00:22:25,922
Wait a minute. Did you just write?

310
00:22:26,680 --> 00:22:28,205
No way!

311
00:22:29,480 --> 00:22:31,642
You want to learn to write more stuff'?

312
00:22:33,440 --> 00:22:35,204
<i>And read too'?</i>

313
00:22:37,440 --> 00:22:38,851
So you can have a voice.

314
00:22:40,200 --> 00:22:42,407
You're some swan, little guy.

315
00:22:44,120 --> 00:22:45,201
He's gone.

316
00:22:45,440 --> 00:22:48,125
He's... He's really, really gone.

317
00:22:48,440 --> 00:22:49,680
It's her fault.

318
00:22:49,920 --> 00:22:51,843
She wouldn't let him play Marco Polo.

319
00:22:52,080 --> 00:22:54,686
And she wouldn't let him play
Duck, Duck, Goose.

320
00:22:54,880 --> 00:22:57,247
It doesn't matter whose fault it is.

321
00:22:57,480 --> 00:22:58,606
What matters is...

322
00:22:58,840 --> 00:22:59,966
...is that he's gone.

323
00:23:00,280 --> 00:23:03,170
I must leave this idyllic lake
and look for him.

324
00:23:03,680 --> 00:23:07,605
Darling, darling, there's just
one little matter to consider.

325
00:23:07,800 --> 00:23:10,246
We have no idea where Louie went.

326
00:23:10,520 --> 00:23:14,445
Well, my birdly instincts
tell me he has gone...

327
00:23:14,680 --> 00:23:17,809
-...south.
- Uh-huh. Well, what about north?

328
00:23:18,040 --> 00:23:19,087
Or <i>east'?</i>

329
00:23:19,320 --> 00:23:20,321
Or west?

330
00:23:20,560 --> 00:23:23,006
Or northeast? Or the southeast?

331
00:23:23,200 --> 00:23:26,090
Or southwest and northwest?

332
00:23:26,600 --> 00:23:28,648
Oh, there are too many directions!

333
00:23:29,040 --> 00:23:31,520
We'll just have to hope
that Louie comes back.

334
00:23:31,800 --> 00:23:34,201
If he ever does come back.

335
00:23:34,400 --> 00:23:39,008
But who will I dive with
if he doesn't come back?

336
00:23:40,480 --> 00:23:42,323
Congratulations, children.

337
00:23:42,600 --> 00:23:47,367
Our special fern is finally ready
for the science fair.

338
00:23:47,800 --> 00:23:50,724
I know we're all looking
forward to the fair.

339
00:23:51,160 --> 00:23:53,128
Aren't we, Mr. Fern'?

340
00:23:53,720 --> 00:23:57,930
That's Mrs. Hammerbotham. She taught
me to read when I was in first grade.

341
00:23:58,560 --> 00:24:02,360
Now remember, boys and girls,
plants have feelings too.

342
00:24:04,960 --> 00:24:06,450
Hello, Sammy.

343
00:24:06,680 --> 00:24:10,207
Did you come to share
your special pet'?

344
00:24:10,520 --> 00:24:15,447
He's not my pet. He has to learn how
to read and write as soon as possible.

345
00:24:15,800 --> 00:24:18,406
Sammy, Sammy, Sammy.

346
00:24:20,360 --> 00:24:23,682
I like the way Sammy
uses his imagination.

347
00:24:24,120 --> 00:24:26,202
Don't you, children?

348
00:24:26,920 --> 00:24:30,242
I'm sorry, Sammy,
but I've never taught a swan.

349
00:24:30,600 --> 00:24:34,207
Oh, he's very well-behaved.
And he won't mess up the room.

350
00:24:34,520 --> 00:24:37,205
He'll even raise his wing
when he has to go to the--

351
00:24:38,160 --> 00:24:42,085
Oh, dear! Now look what's happened!

352
00:24:42,360 --> 00:24:43,964
Oh, Sammy, don't you see.

353
00:24:44,160 --> 00:24:47,801
We can't have this swan in class.

354
00:24:48,160 --> 00:24:51,448
But you were the one
who taught me to respect...

355
00:24:51,680 --> 00:24:54,206
-...the differences of others.
- Well, yes, dear.

356
00:24:54,480 --> 00:24:55,891
You said the world
is a rainbow...

357
00:24:56,120 --> 00:24:58,043
-...of different colours.
- Different colours.

358
00:24:58,240 --> 00:25:00,447
- Different races.
- Different races.

359
00:25:00,640 --> 00:25:02,881
- Different creeds.
- Different creeds.

360
00:25:03,160 --> 00:25:06,528
- Different species.
- Different species!

361
00:25:07,080 --> 00:25:08,605
Different species?

362
00:25:08,800 --> 00:25:11,007
Did I say that?

363
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:17,324
Sammy, sometimes Mrs. Hammerbotham
says what she thinks she means...

364
00:25:17,560 --> 00:25:22,487
...but that she doesn't actually mean
to mean. Do you know what I mean?

365
00:25:23,120 --> 00:25:27,170
Please. You can't discriminate
against him just because he's poultry.

366
00:25:30,480 --> 00:25:34,849
Oh, what a little darling.

367
00:25:35,360 --> 00:25:36,805
Well...

368
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:41,927
Now, I guess we do need
a new science project.

369
00:25:42,360 --> 00:25:44,124
What do you say, children?

370
00:25:44,320 --> 00:25:46,402
Yes!

371
00:25:47,280 --> 00:25:48,691
I'm in first grade.

372
00:25:49,080 --> 00:25:51,606
This will be your seat.

373
00:25:53,680 --> 00:25:57,765
Let's remember to keep
our wings to ourselves.

374
00:26:08,640 --> 00:26:12,611
We must work on our fine motor skills.

375
00:26:13,280 --> 00:26:16,045
Is it time for recess?

376
00:26:24,240 --> 00:26:25,241
Oh, dear.

377
00:26:25,720 --> 00:26:29,202
If only our eyes weren't
on the opposite sides of our head.

378
00:26:29,560 --> 00:26:32,370
But I like the way
you're trying, little guy.

379
00:26:36,400 --> 00:26:41,327
"One fine morning in the month of May,
Stuart arose early."

380
00:26:48,160 --> 00:26:49,605
<i>That's you'?</i>

381
00:26:49,800 --> 00:26:52,121
Wow! You have a name.

382
00:26:52,360 --> 00:26:54,089
All right, little guy.

383
00:26:54,320 --> 00:26:55,970
I mean, all right, Louie.

384
00:26:56,160 --> 00:26:58,845
Well done, Louie.
Oh, what a special day this is.

385
00:26:59,080 --> 00:27:02,004
- All right, Louie.
- Oh, you see, children...

386
00:27:02,240 --> 00:27:05,084
...if we try our very, very best...

387
00:27:05,320 --> 00:27:08,483
...we can do anything
we set our minds to.

388
00:27:14,480 --> 00:27:17,802
Good luck, Louie.
I'll be counting the days till camp.

389
00:27:18,160 --> 00:27:22,245
Wow! "Honour Swan
at Billings Elementary School."

390
00:27:22,720 --> 00:27:23,926
That's me.

391
00:27:24,160 --> 00:27:25,286
Thanks a million.

392
00:27:31,480 --> 00:27:33,130
Hey, I got it covered.

393
00:27:33,480 --> 00:27:34,891
Here comes the great one.

394
00:27:35,120 --> 00:27:36,645
- Hey!
- You snooze you lose.

395
00:27:37,640 --> 00:27:39,608
Got it! Open, I'm open!

396
00:27:42,480 --> 00:27:43,606
- Oops.
- Butterfingers.

397
00:27:43,800 --> 00:27:45,723
She scores.

398
00:27:46,160 --> 00:27:48,208
Victory dance.

399
00:27:49,680 --> 00:27:51,125
Ko... Ko...

400
00:27:51,360 --> 00:27:52,646
Ko-hoh! Look!

401
00:27:53,240 --> 00:27:55,527
Look! Can it be'?

402
00:27:55,760 --> 00:27:59,207
Miracle of miracles, it's Louie!

403
00:27:59,400 --> 00:28:03,246
Louie, my Louie, oh, you're so big.

404
00:28:03,480 --> 00:28:05,448
But so thin.

405
00:28:05,640 --> 00:28:07,529
Have you been getting enough to eat'?

406
00:28:07,960 --> 00:28:10,042
Louie, my son...

407
00:28:10,280 --> 00:28:15,207
...no one can imagine the extent
of our joy at seeing you again.

408
00:28:15,400 --> 00:28:17,880
I'm sure I speak for everyone here--

409
00:28:18,120 --> 00:28:21,283
Perhaps, you could speak
for everyone later, darling.

410
00:28:24,320 --> 00:28:27,051
What's that weird thing
on your neck, Louie'?

411
00:28:28,040 --> 00:28:29,804
Wait until they see this.

412
00:28:30,320 --> 00:28:31,606
"Hi there."

413
00:28:34,080 --> 00:28:37,766
Wha--'? Do you think Louie
has gone cuckoo, Mother'?

414
00:28:38,080 --> 00:28:39,809
Well, he was always a creep.

415
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:43,607
Now he's a creep
with a little baby bib.

416
00:28:43,960 --> 00:28:46,406
- What is he doing?
- Hi there.

417
00:28:47,720 --> 00:28:50,564
Hear me, Serena. I did this for you.

418
00:28:51,280 --> 00:28:53,282
What are you trying to say, Louie'?

419
00:28:58,320 --> 00:28:59,890
Nothing's changed.

420
00:29:00,120 --> 00:29:02,600
They still can't understand me.

421
00:29:10,840 --> 00:29:13,127
How could I have been so stupid?

422
00:29:21,920 --> 00:29:25,606
This, my son, is your trumpet.

423
00:29:26,680 --> 00:29:28,808
If you learn to play it, Louie...

424
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:32,800
...you will be able to ko-hoh
like every other swan.

425
00:29:34,080 --> 00:29:36,048
May the hills echo...

426
00:29:36,280 --> 00:29:39,602
...with your new voice, my son.

427
00:29:55,440 --> 00:29:58,410
Man, even for a rodent
this is tough on the ears.

428
00:29:58,920 --> 00:30:01,400
I'll never learn to play this thing.

429
00:30:09,520 --> 00:30:11,010
Now come on, try it again.

430
00:30:12,040 --> 00:30:14,646
Man, there's a voice inside of you...

431
00:30:14,880 --> 00:30:16,928
...that is dying to come out.

432
00:30:17,120 --> 00:30:21,409
Now come on, give me
some of that sweet, sweet music.

433
00:30:28,080 --> 00:30:30,321
Oh, man, anybody got earplugs?

434
00:30:34,240 --> 00:30:35,082
Oh, yeah.

435
00:30:36,040 --> 00:30:37,769
<i>Hey, hey</i>

436
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:41,288
<i>- Everybody's shakin' 'em
- Come on, let's jam</i>

437
00:30:41,480 --> 00:30:45,041
<i>And groove to the beat
You gotta find your feet and swing</i>

438
00:30:45,640 --> 00:30:47,563
<i>- I got to say
- I got to say</i>

439
00:30:47,800 --> 00:30:50,644
<i>- How in love I am
- She's in love</i>

440
00:30:50,840 --> 00:30:54,731
<i>With the music I hear
Everybody's here and sing</i>

441
00:30:55,960 --> 00:30:58,088
<i>Join us girls and boys</i>

442
00:30:58,320 --> 00:31:00,800
<i>Screamin' and making noise</i>

443
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:03,446
<i>The music goes like this</i>

444
00:31:06,200 --> 00:31:08,567
<i>- I'm going, I'm going
- Come on in</i>

445
00:31:08,800 --> 00:31:09,881
Join, come on

446
00:31:10,120 --> 00:31:14,444
<i>Make a big line now
Come, come, come on, sing</i>

447
00:31:19,840 --> 00:31:21,524
I have to find my voice too.

448
00:31:21,760 --> 00:31:23,842
I just have to.

449
00:31:34,360 --> 00:31:35,850
Yes.

450
00:31:39,920 --> 00:31:42,844
- Yes.
- Wow! Louie'?

451
00:31:43,040 --> 00:31:45,247
Are you the one making that sound?

452
00:31:45,880 --> 00:31:47,245
I like it.

453
00:31:47,440 --> 00:31:49,044
Play some more.

454
00:31:51,240 --> 00:31:52,651
Thank you, Louie.

455
00:31:52,960 --> 00:31:56,851
I don't know what it is,
but it's really sweet.

456
00:32:07,440 --> 00:32:08,851
Serena!

457
00:32:13,280 --> 00:32:14,520
Hi, Daddy.

458
00:32:16,920 --> 00:32:18,490
Oh, there's Boyd.

459
00:32:18,720 --> 00:32:20,563
Boyd! Maurice here!

460
00:32:20,800 --> 00:32:22,086
Serena!

461
00:32:22,600 --> 00:32:25,080
Serena, say hello to Boyd.

462
00:32:25,320 --> 00:32:26,401
Hi, Boyd.

463
00:32:26,880 --> 00:32:29,451
Well, hello, Serena.

464
00:32:29,640 --> 00:32:34,407
You know, Boyd just happens to be
the best trumpeter in Montana.

465
00:32:35,560 --> 00:32:37,130
Boyd, how about it, huh'?

466
00:32:37,360 --> 00:32:40,489
Let's hear those vocal cords vibrate.

467
00:32:40,960 --> 00:32:43,531
Ko-hoh!

468
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:47,843
Incredible.

469
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:51,526
Serena, Serena,
come along, come along.

470
00:32:51,760 --> 00:32:53,444
Boyd is joining us for dinner.

471
00:33:06,120 --> 00:33:07,121
<i>Attention units.</i>

472
00:33:07,360 --> 00:33:10,045
Be on the lookout for a swan thief.

473
00:33:10,880 --> 00:33:12,962
That's him. That's the one.

474
00:33:13,400 --> 00:33:14,401
I'll get you!

475
00:33:17,800 --> 00:33:19,643
Stop, thief!

476
00:33:19,960 --> 00:33:22,088
<i>Swan thief spotted downtown.</i>

477
00:33:24,360 --> 00:33:26,727
<i>You are surrounded.
Stop where you are.</i>

478
00:33:27,720 --> 00:33:30,644
It's that swan thief!

479
00:33:32,320 --> 00:33:33,560
They're pursuing me!

480
00:33:33,800 --> 00:33:36,644
They're pursuing me with a vengeance!

481
00:33:39,600 --> 00:33:41,329
They're going to lock me up!

482
00:33:41,560 --> 00:33:44,006
Darling, it was just a dream.

483
00:33:44,320 --> 00:33:47,051
No! Nonsense, no!
They were after me!

484
00:33:47,280 --> 00:33:51,490
With shotguns and footcuffs
and wingwhoppers and...

485
00:33:51,720 --> 00:33:53,563
What's got into you, darling?

486
00:33:53,760 --> 00:33:58,243
Oh, my dear, my dear, my dear,
I am nothing but a common criminal.

487
00:33:58,480 --> 00:33:59,845
A thief!

488
00:34:00,760 --> 00:34:05,084
You see, I procured the trumpet
without paying for it.

489
00:34:05,600 --> 00:34:07,250
You mean you... You...

490
00:34:07,440 --> 00:34:08,566
<i>You stole it'?</i>

491
00:34:08,800 --> 00:34:12,122
It is deplorable, but true.

492
00:34:12,360 --> 00:34:14,362
But you did it for love.

493
00:34:14,720 --> 00:34:19,248
But I sacrificed my honour.

494
00:34:19,600 --> 00:34:22,490
Now I will never sleep in peace again.

495
00:34:22,720 --> 00:34:26,202
There, there, dear.
You did it for Louie.

496
00:34:27,040 --> 00:34:29,122
I'm sorry, Father.

497
00:34:29,360 --> 00:34:31,249
I'll get your honour back.

498
00:34:31,440 --> 00:34:32,646
I will.

499
00:34:39,320 --> 00:34:43,041
This is the heart
I never got to give you, Serena.

500
00:34:43,960 --> 00:34:45,291
Goodbye.

501
00:34:45,520 --> 00:34:46,521
I'll miss you.

502
00:35:10,960 --> 00:35:13,042
<i>Welcome, campers.</i>

503
00:35:13,760 --> 00:35:17,082
<i>- Please unpack all your things.
- It's great to be back.</i>

